; font-weight:bold">some regulatory functions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">, controlling the Highways Agency through a licence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> will need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">that the company</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">’s management face</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> incentives to become more efficient.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Some flexibility will be needed to allow for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">(budget or output) adjustments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> in response to changing circumstances within the funding period. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">In the long run, independent regulation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">could</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">facilitate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> private investment in the sector.</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:20pt 7.1pt 15pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:15pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Oxera</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is delighted to have the opportunity to respond to the Transport Select Committee’s call for written evidence to the inquiry into the strategic road network (SRN).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Oxera</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">advises companies, policymakers, regulators and lawyers on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">economic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> issue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> connected with competition, finance or regulation, including in the infrastructure space. We have been doing this for more than three decades, gathering deep and wide-ranging knowledge as we expand into new sectors. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This experience has provided </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Oxera</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with an unmatched knowledge of regulatory and financial economics as applied to the transport sector. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given our expertise, this note focuses on the following questions raised in the inquiry’s terms of reference.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">How </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should the Highways Agency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be reformed to make it ‘the world’s leading highway operator’? What roles should government and the private sector play to ensure better management of the SRN? (Sections 2 and 3)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">How reliable is the government’s forecast for growth in demand for the SRN? How should the government deal with uncertainty in its forecast?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Section 4)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">What mechanisms are there for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment to increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors? Are there good examples from other countries that could be applied in the UK? </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Section 5)</span></p><p style="margin:20pt 7.1pt 15pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:15pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">Impact of the recently announced reforms</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:459pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#e6e1e8; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:459pt"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The reforms should help to support future economic growth by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">facilitating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> a more efficient allocation of resources and allowing for a longer-term perspective to be reflected in investment decisions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">reater commercialism</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> may also generate some productive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">efficiencies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The government’s ‘Action for Roads’ paper lays out several reforms to the governance of the SRN, including:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he corpora</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tisation of the Highways Agency (HA);</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ong-term funding certainty, similar to the statement of funds available in the GB rail sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enhanced budgetary flexibility; </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> publication of a roads investment strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overarching long-term objective for reforming the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">deliver, or to support,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> future economic growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The announced reforms could be expected to contribute to this objective by facilitating better targeted, longer-term investment decisions. There are two main explanations for this:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">greater independence from central government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould facilitate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a more efficient allocation of resources </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by allowing decisions to be made on an independent basis, with less influence from political motivations;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">greater</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> long-term funding certainty </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should lead to a better balance between short- and long-term investment needs, by allowing the HA to make decisions with a longer-term perspective.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As well as targeting economic growth, an important objective of the reforms is to ensure that the governance of the SRN is providing value for money for the taxpayer. In his review of the sector, Alan Cook estimated potential efficiencies to be in the region of £200m per annum (in addition to the commitments made by the HA as part of the 2010 Spending Review).</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some productive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">efficiencies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> may result directly from corporatisation—and the more commercial perspective that results—but there remains a broader question as to how appropriate efficiency incentives can be introduced for a company with a non-equity ownership structure. This is considered in the next section.</span></p><p style="margin:20pt 7.1pt 15pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:15pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">The role of the government</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:459pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#e6e1e8; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:459pt"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">There will need to be oversight of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">HA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">’s performance—the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> could take on some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">quasi-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">regulatory functions, with a road user champion being set up to promote the interests of users.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">High</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">quality information will be needed to assess the company’s performance. This will require legislation and resources.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">There </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">will need to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> be some flexibility to adjust the funding settlement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">there are material changes in circumstance that are outside of managerial control.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The government should set out a strategy for the road network as a whole, explaining the interaction between the SRN and the local road network.</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> could</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">take on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">some oversight role in ensuring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">highways company acts towards achieving the Roads Investment Strategy and is compliant with its funding settlement (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> perform some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">quasi-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">regulatory function). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Indeed, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Oxera</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">understands that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> intends to control the HA through a licence and the signing of a framework agreement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he contents of the licence and the oversight of the organisation have not yet been determined. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In carrying out this role, it would be important for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to ensure that its interventions are proportionate, and that (subject to meetings its performance specification) the HA has sufficient flexibility to foster the benefits of greater commercialism.</span></p><p style="margin:15pt 7.1pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">I</span><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ncentives and enforcement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For the majority of companies, shareholders </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stand to gain financially where the company is able to become more efficient. Hence, shareholders </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">exert pressure on management to achieve efficiencies.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The HA’s sole shareholder will be the government, which means that these pressures are unlikely to be replicated fully. Consideration will therefore have to be given to how management can best be incentivised to achieve efficiencies. This is closely linked to how the new company, and its management, is held to account for its performance—in particular, what penalties would arise if the company were to fail (continually) to meet the terms of the performance specification? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These issues are not unique to the roads sector—</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">indeed,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> they have vexed the GB rail industry given Network Rail’s non-conventional corporate structure.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the rail sector, management incentives have been provided by linking pay to the performance of the company relative to regulatory measures of performance. Indeed, for there to be efficiency incentives similar to those in an equity-financed company, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will have to influence the HA’s board. Performance-related pay is likely to be one of the simplest and most effective means of providing incentives at the board level. However, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will need to consider how it can design the licence to limit any disconnect between the level of senior bonuses and its assessment of the HA’s performance. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Experience from other sectors suggests that, as well as performance-related pay, the following arrangements could be considered.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Linking the level of funding to the delivery of certain performance metrics</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For example, funding coul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d be withheld if the HA fails</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to meets its performance targets.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Provide reputational incentives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> For non-equity companies, reputational incentives can be strong motivators. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Special administration arrangements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Arrangements could be put in place to allow the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to remove and replace the senior management team at the HA, either if certain predefined thresholds are breached or at the discretion of the Secretary of State for Transport. The threat of such arrangements being enforced would provide strong incentives to the HA management team.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has indicated that it is looking at options for a road user ‘watchdog’ or ‘champion’. Such a body would be expected to monitor the new company’s performance and identify if it is failing to meet targets. This might include periodically benchmarking the company’s costs and efficiency relative to other UK infrastructure managers and international road companies. More broadly, the watchdog or champion would act as the voice of the road user, ensuring that road users’ priorities are reflected in the HA’s decision-making processes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Setting up a watchdog or consumer champion would be expected to enhance the reputational incentives for management to exert effort. Indeed, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he likelihood is that the body’s publication of performance figures would, over time, receive widespread media attention (as is the case with information on Network Rail’s performance), providing further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">incentive for management to ensure that the company meets its targets. The watchdog could also play a role if funding were to be linked to meeting performance standards (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, funding could be linked to the number of complaints received by the watchdog).</span></p><p style="margin:15pt 7.1pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Uncertainty mechanisms</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">financial discipline required from the new company will change from that under the current model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. If the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> steps in to provide additional funding where the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is being inefficiently operated, efficiency incentive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s will be considerably weakened. To the extent possible, therefore, the HA needs to operate under a hard budget constraint.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is, however, also a risk that factors beyond the control of the management team will create a situation where the company is unable to meet the terms of the performance specification under the existing funding settlement. This could, for example, be the result of an external shock that leads to the HA facing significantly higher costs than previously forecast. There is thus a trade-off between establishing a ‘hard’ budget constraint, thereby providing strong efficiency incentives, and ensuring that there is flexibility to respond to changing circumstances within the funding period.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It may therefore be necessary to specify the circumstances under which the HA can ask for additional funding (or a reduced performance specification), and to outline the appeals process, should the company find that it cannot live with a settlement. There are well-established practices from economic regulation of other infrastructure sectors in the UK that can be applied to provide the new company and its management with appropriate safeguards against non-controllable factors, while preserving efficiency incentives.</span></p><p style="margin:15pt 7.1pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Information provision</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is to perform a quasi-regulatory role, it will need good</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">data on the SRN’s costs and assets. This raises two issues:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has limited information-gathering powers at present;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">experience from other network companies that have been subject to privatisation or corporatisation suggests that i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nitial information is likely to be limited or insufficiently detailed for this purpos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e. For example, the GB </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rail industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> still developing information databases nearly 20 years after privatisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">egislation and resources</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will both be needed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to overcome this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> information asymmetry. There will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">need to be cl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">arity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ho is responsible for overseeing the collection, accuracy and monitoring of data</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">what information should be provided and at what level of detail;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">how</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> frequently the HA should be required to supply this information.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will need to consider how it would enforce requirements or provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">incentives for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the HA to produce better quality information.</span></p><p style="margin:15pt 7.1pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Resourcing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The body charged with overseeing the HA’s performance will need to have sufficient resources and qualified staff to carry out its activities. The design of the accountability regime should therefore be consistent with the availability of such resources. If the new body is to form part of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, it will need to be set up as a distinct entity within the Department, separate from the existing Road Strategy and Charging division. There could also be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">limitations on the information that can be transferred between these two parts of the organisation. Over time, this part of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> could, if desired, become a separate roads regulator (see section 5).</span></p><p style="margin:15pt 7.1pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Interaction with local road network</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Almost all road journeys start and end on the local road network. There is thus a clear interaction between the operation and management of the SRN and that of the local road network. The Roads Investment Strategy should set out how investment in the SRN fits into the government’s vision for the development of the road network as a whole. (local authorities)</span></p><p style="margin:20pt 7.1pt 15pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:15pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">DfT’s</span><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold"> demand forecasting</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:459pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#e6e1e8; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:459pt"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> is forecasting traffic growth of 46% on the SRN between 2010 and 2040.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The assumptions underlying the model have been tested by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> and appear to be sound.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ould give further thought to the effect that cultural change and parking constraints will have on future demand, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ould provide forecasts at a greater level of geographic disaggregation.</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> latest forecasts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> project</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that traffic growth will be slow up to 2015 in line with low projected GDP growth and high fuel costs. Faster economic growth and significantly decreased fuel costs of driving resulting from rapid fuel efficiency improvements are then expected to lead to a rise in traffic of 19% from 2015 to 2025. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Traffic growth is forecast to slow po</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t-2025 as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the rate of improvements in vehicle fuel efficiencies declines</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Between 2010 and 2040, traffic on the SRN is expected to grow by 46%.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> projections of trends in road traffic and congestion are based on its National Transport Model (NTM). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Under the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NTM, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he main </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">factors influencing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">car traffic (in terms of vehicle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">miles) are population, GDP per capital, and fuel cost. The model currently assumes that:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a 1% growth in population leads to a 0.95% increase in car traffic;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a 1% increase in GDP per capita leads to a 0.28% increase in car traffic;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 1% increase in fuel cost leads to a 0.30% reduction in car traffic.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has tested these assumptions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by ‘updating’ previous forecasts for outturn population, GDP per capita and fuel cost data. This analysis has shown that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NTM </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">matches outturn traffic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">closely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, to further improve its road traffic forecasts, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> could focus on the following:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Understanding c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ultural change.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The take-up of driving among young men has decreased significantly in recent years as a result of higher driving costs (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, insurance and fuel costs). There is also evidence of a partial modal shift towards rail, particularly for business travel, given the reduction in company car usage.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> An understanding is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">needed of how cultural changes, particularly for young people, will affect future road demand.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Parking constraints</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A potential weakness of the NTM is that it does not factor in constraints on the availability of parking spaces. Decisions on whether to make a car journey are likely to be heavily influenced by the ability to park at the destination. Consequently, better understanding is needed of how the availability of parking spaces will affect future road demand.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Greater geographic disaggregation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> For decision-making purposes, there are likely to be clear benefits from having greater spatial detail on the breakdown of demand—for example, an understanding of the routes on which road traffic is likely to grow rapidly and where this could lead to congestion. </span></p><p style="margin:20pt 7.1pt 15pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:15pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">Securing private investment</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:459pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#e6e1e8; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:459pt"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Independent regulation is likely to be a necessary condition for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> attracting private finance to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">SRN</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Implementing regulation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">will ultimately be dependent on the creation of a charging framework that allows investors to recover their costs plus </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">return on their investment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The oversight options adopted now should not prevent regulation from being </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">introduced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> in the future.</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the long run, there is no reason why there could not be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(a more significant amount of) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">private investment in the SRN.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> As in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">electricity, gas, telecoms, and water sectors, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">establishing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an independent regulator is likely to be a necessary condition for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">accessing private financing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Indeed, independent regulation—combined with credible regulatory powers—is typically associated with a number of benefits, as follows.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Investor reassurance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Independent regulation provides a means of reducing political manipulation and enhancing stability, thereby providing reassurance to investors. As noted by the Department of Business, Innovation and Skills:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 35.45pt 11pt 36.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In the UK, the statutory framework of independent economic regulation encapsulates a commitment by the UK Government not to intervene other than in clearly specified ways. Independence helps provide stability and consistency over time. This in turn helps to anchor market participants’ expectations and increase the predictability of regulatory outcomes.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sector-specific knowledge and expertise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK regulators have accumulated a sector-specific knowledge and expertise that civil servants, who are likely to move between</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sectors more frequently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, are less likely to possess. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 22.7pt; text-indent:-22.7pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">–</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Cheaper </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(debt) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">finance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Credit rating agencies consider independent regulation to provide stability and transparency and therefore regulated companies are often able to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">achieve a better credit rating for a given credit metric</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> than non-regulated companies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Currently, a major barrier to the introduction of more private capital into the roads sector is the source of the revenues with which to remunerate investors. P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rivate sector investors will not provide finance unless they will be compensated with a return on their investment.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would require</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> establish</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ment of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dedicated revenue stream</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, either through direct user charging—which does not appear to be politically palatable in the short run—or a hypothecation of road taxes. An appropriate charging framework will therefore need to be developed before large-scale private capital can be accessed for the SRN.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the meantime, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will need to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">look to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the oversight model adopted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> now </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the creation of a watchdog) retains the flexibility required to establish</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> independent regulat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ion, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should the charging issue be resolved over time.</span></p><p style="margin:20pt 7.1pt 15pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:15pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-56.7pt"><span style="color:#663366; display:inline; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The arguments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">raised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in this paper are outlined in the table below.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 63.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-63.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary of conclusions</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:96.88%"><tr style="height:16.15pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#663366; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:bottom; width:50%"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">Inquiry question</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#663366; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:bottom; width:50%"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">Oxera’s</span><span style="color:#663366; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold"> response</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:16.15pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#bfc6d1; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#663366; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:50%"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">How should the HA be reformed to make it the world’s leading highway operator’? </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">What roles should government and the private sector play to ensure better management of the SRN?</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#bfc6d1; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#663366; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:50%"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Broadly speaking, the reforms announced in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">DfT’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> ‘Action for Roads’ are an important step in the right direction. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">In particular, the reforms should allow the HA to base decisions on a longer-term, more commercial perspective with greater independence from political decision-making.</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:16.15pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#bfc6d1; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#bfc6d1; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:50%"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">How reliable is the government’s forecast for growth in demand for the SRN? How should the government deal with uncertainty in its forecast?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#bfc6d1; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#bfc6d1; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:50%"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> has tested the assumptions underlying the NTM and has concluded they are sound. However, improvements could be made to better understand cultural change, model the impact of parking space availability, and develop greater spatial detail.</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:17pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#663366; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#bfc6d1; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:50%"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">What mechanisms are there for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">overnment to increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors? </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Are there good examples from other countries that could be applied in the UK?</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#663366; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#bfc6d1; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:50%"><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Independent regulation facilitates private investment by providing reassurance to investors that they will fully recover their costs while earning a fair return on their investments.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Independent regulation would therefore typically be expected to reduce financing costs.</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 99.25pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#d14514; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:left;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">2</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#939598; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">:</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Cook, A. (2011), ‘A fresh start for the Strategic Road Network: Managing our roads better to drive economic growth, boost innovation and give road users more for their money’, November.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Department for Transport (2013), ‘Road Transport Forecasts 2013 – Results from the Department for Transport’s National Transport Model’, July 29th, p. 22, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> 3.3.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Le Vine, S. and Jones, P. (2012), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">On the move: Making sense of car and train travel trends in Britain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, prepared for the Office of Rail Regulation, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Independent Transport Commission, Transport Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> and the RAC Foundation, December.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">This topic has been covered in greater detail in a recent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Agenda</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> article published on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Oxera’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> website: ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">At</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> a crossroads: the future of the strategic road network’, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Agenda</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, August 20th 2013, available at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">http://www.oxera.com/Oxera/media/Oxera/downloads/Agenda/UK-road-reform.pdf?ext=.pdf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (2011), ‘Principles for Economic Regulation’, April, p. 7, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> 23.</span></p></body></html>